WEBVTT

00:11.000 --> 00:12.720
(Distant sirens)

00:12.800 --> 00:17.320
MAN (on TV): Olof Palme, Prime Minister
of Sweden, was assassinated last night

00:17.400 --> 00:19.120
while walking home
from the cinema with his wife Lisbet.

00:19.440 --> 00:21.840
The assassination occurred
in Sveavägen street in central Stockholm

00:22.240 --> 00:24.560
ANC Safe House, Cape Town, South Africa

00:24.640 --> 00:26.200
at 11:21 p.m., Central European Time.

00:26.560 --> 00:29.680
Lisbet Palme was also
wounded by a second shot, but survived.

00:30.080 --> 00:33.040
The couple
did not have bodyguards at the time.

00:34.240 --> 00:36.080
MAN: Come away from
the window Rose, please.

00:36.920 --> 00:40.000
-Someone might see you standing there.
-Or I'll see them first!

00:41.080 --> 00:44.000
Sanjev is right, please step back
from the window, it's dangerous.

00:44.400 --> 00:47.200
You should've thought about that
before you got Rose involved in this.

00:47.600 --> 00:50.240
It's only a matter of time
before the mercenaries track her down.

00:50.640 --> 00:53.960
-Sanjev, stop.
-You need to leave the country.

00:54.720 --> 00:58.640
We will. We're headed North
to find a new buyer.

00:58.720 --> 01:00.680
Who's that?

01:01.080 --> 01:03.920
The communists from the MPLA
who defend the refinery.

01:04.000 --> 01:05.000
(Dog barking in distance)

01:05.400 --> 01:07.600
You're going to Angola? Over land?

01:08.000 --> 01:11.200
With Rose and a load of weapons?

01:11.840 --> 01:13.280
Through the border war, are you crazy?

01:13.360 --> 01:16.960
♪♪

01:17.040 --> 01:19.600
( dog barking in distance)

01:20.760 --> 01:23.840
You might as well just walk
straight into the Wild Geese Club.

01:23.920 --> 01:24.920
(Man yelling in distance)

01:25.000 --> 01:27.920
South Africa is a kind of paradise
for mercenary killers of all stripes.

01:29.520 --> 01:31.640
Ex-Foreign Legion,
ex-SAS, ex-Green Berets,

01:32.040 --> 01:34.920
all ex-something, all brutal,
all white.

01:35.000 --> 01:37.560
I wouldn't be surprised if Olof Palme
was taken out by one of them.

01:37.960 --> 01:40.000
Why would a South African mercenary
go after

01:40.080 --> 01:41.840
the Prime Minister of Sweden
in Stockholm?

01:41.920 --> 01:43.840
Their kill list
goes way beyond our borders.

01:44.240 --> 01:47.920
Palme gave a speech
denouncing apartheid only days ago.

01:48.800 --> 01:50.280
♪♪

01:50.360 --> 01:54.000
Many of them are killing blacks,
some communists.

01:54.400 --> 01:56.440
Or their favorite: black communists.

01:56.560 --> 01:58.760
(Dog growling, man screaming)

02:01.040 --> 02:05.040
The good news is
they'll do anything for money.

02:05.160 --> 02:07.560
(Man screaming)

02:09.120 --> 02:11.000
(Fly buzzing)

02:13.280 --> 02:15.160
(Indistinct news report on radio)

02:19.000 --> 02:20.880
(Glass bottles clanging)

02:24.680 --> 02:25.920
Hello.

02:29.960 --> 02:31.800
What's the best way into Angola?

02:32.160 --> 02:33.880
Is that a riddle?

02:41.600 --> 02:42.680
(Exhales)

02:45.720 --> 02:48.600
It's treacherous over land
through the border war.

02:49.120 --> 02:51.360
-But most people take a plane.
-Not a plane.

02:51.720 --> 02:53.280
-Well, a boat then.
-Not a boat.

02:53.680 --> 02:55.640
-Then you need Banks.
-Who?

02:56.040 --> 02:58.000
No one knows the border lines like Banks.

02:58.400 --> 03:01.640
He could navigate his way through
that war zone with a baby in his arms.

03:01.720 --> 03:03.320
♪♪

03:03.400 --> 03:05.080
Over there.

03:05.800 --> 03:07.760
The guy in the cage.

03:09.320 --> 03:10.960
Take your money back.

03:14.880 --> 03:17.160
(Ventilators whirring, fly buzzing)

03:18.640 --> 03:20.840
That's my good girl.

03:22.640 --> 03:24.440
Yes, a good girl.

03:27.600 --> 03:29.160
Excuse me?

03:30.000 --> 03:31.520
Are you Banks?

03:36.040 --> 03:38.200
The bartender tells us
you're the man we're looking for.

03:38.600 --> 03:40.720
The bartender's an asshole.

03:41.720 --> 03:43.960
(Dog growling)

03:45.680 --> 03:47.440
Don't worry about the dog.

03:48.000 --> 03:50.080
She only bites blacks.

03:53.160 --> 03:56.040
When she was a baby,
I used to put her in a bag

03:56.120 --> 03:58.320
and beat her with a stick.

03:59.360 --> 04:01.600
Then I'd get a black guy to open the bag,

04:02.000 --> 04:06.280
the key being the first face she'd see
after being beaten would be black.

04:06.680 --> 04:08.480
That's how she learned to hate them.

04:08.560 --> 04:09.560
(Dog barking)

04:11.720 --> 04:13.880
You sure you don't have
a black grandmother?

04:16.040 --> 04:17.320
I doubt it.

04:18.480 --> 04:20.480
What exactly do you need me for?

04:20.880 --> 04:24.680
To get us into the country
to this refinery.

04:25.440 --> 04:26.440
Safely.

04:28.960 --> 04:33.120
You know the two worst things that can
happen to a guy in my line of business?

04:33.600 --> 04:36.040
Getting killed and not getting paid.

04:36.120 --> 04:40.440
And not necessarily in that order.
So I would like payment up front.

04:42.120 --> 04:45.720
Well, we were thinking about
giving you a share afterwards.

04:46.760 --> 04:48.440
(German) I think you're done here.

04:48.520 --> 04:50.600
♪♪

05:05.960 --> 05:07.480
(Door opens)

05:07.560 --> 05:10.040
(Door closes)

05:21.680 --> 05:23.800
(Street atmosphere,
male and female groaning)

05:35.000 --> 05:38.000
(Dog barking, bird chirping,
children's voices in distance)

05:38.520 --> 05:40.000
And?

05:40.120 --> 05:42.760
(Ship horn, seagulls)

05:42.840 --> 05:44.160
Huh.

05:44.960 --> 05:46.560
He'll do it without the cash.

05:48.080 --> 05:50.280
But he wants a diamond.

05:50.360 --> 05:52.240
Two carats.

05:52.720 --> 05:54.160
Great.

05:54.880 --> 05:59.720
Let's just go it alone. Where are we going
to get a huge diamond? Dig it up?

06:00.040 --> 06:03.440
Didn't you say your tooth ached?

06:04.120 --> 06:05.120
No. Why?

06:05.200 --> 06:08.560
Dr. Winkelmann's diamond necklace
was at least two carats.

06:08.640 --> 06:09.720
(Huffs)

06:09.800 --> 06:11.000
I hate dentists.

06:12.480 --> 06:14.320
(Subtle, atmospheric sounds)

06:16.480 --> 06:19.480
("Major Tom Coming Home" by Peter
Schilling) ♪ Four, three, two, one ♪

06:19.560 --> 06:22.080
♪ Earth below us ♪

06:22.400 --> 06:25.320
♪ Drifting, falling ♪

06:25.400 --> 06:28.320
♪ Floating weightless ♪

06:28.400 --> 06:32.560
♪ Calling, calling home ♪

06:41.560 --> 06:45.320
♪ Calling, calling home ♪

06:51.920 --> 06:53.440
MAN (on TV): The Secretary General
of the East German Communist Party

06:53.520 --> 06:55.840
East German Foreign Intelligence Service
HQ, East Berlin, East Germany

06:55.920 --> 06:57.240
Erich Honecker,

06:57.320 --> 07:00.720
welcomes the Secretary General
of the Communist Central Committee,

07:00.800 --> 07:05.480
Mikhail Gorbachev,
on East German land.

07:06.240 --> 07:08.040
(Knocking)

07:08.640 --> 07:10.280
Comrade Schweppenstette,

07:10.360 --> 07:12.760
could you help me to review these files?

07:12.840 --> 07:15.560
Since my promotion,
I've been totally overwhelmed.

07:15.880 --> 07:17.760
I've got my hands full.

07:18.600 --> 07:23.520
Sometimes we wonder:
Have we been too self-critical?

07:23.600 --> 07:26.480
Are we just feeding
anti-Communist propaganda?

07:26.560 --> 07:30.560
Those fireside chats with Reagan
clouded Gorbachev's mind.

07:30.640 --> 07:33.200
Or the CIA spiked his vodka.

07:35.640 --> 07:36.680
(Exhales)

07:36.760 --> 07:39.240
Where do we stand in all this?

07:40.000 --> 07:41.720
Alone.

07:42.200 --> 07:43.280
The realistic evaluation...

07:43.360 --> 07:44.480
All alone.

07:44.560 --> 07:48.880
... was the starting point for
the elaboration of a constructive program

07:49.120 --> 07:51.680
Its centerpiece is the acceleration

07:51.760 --> 07:54.920
of the socioeconomic development
of our country,

07:55.000 --> 07:57.240
which is justified
by the decisions of the Congress,

07:57.320 --> 07:59.520
and the new version of the Party program.

08:08.720 --> 08:10.680
(Dog barking in distance)

08:12.760 --> 08:15.480
Why such a long line?
No meat today?

08:15.560 --> 08:17.920
Would you like no chicken today?
Or no schnitzel?

08:18.000 --> 08:19.520
(Laughter, baby crying)

08:19.600 --> 08:22.160
The pantyhose won't be delivered
for another two hours.

08:22.480 --> 08:25.000
-What?
-Everyone here for pantyhose move right...

08:25.080 --> 08:27.440
-No way!
-... and make room for other customers.

08:27.520 --> 08:28.600
Two hours?

08:28.680 --> 08:31.000
My wife can forget about pantyhose.

08:32.040 --> 08:34.840
This isn't Romania.
You have everything you need.

08:34.920 --> 08:36.960
-If you say so.
-Yes.

08:38.680 --> 08:40.880
(Background chatter)

08:40.960 --> 08:42.120
Excuse me.

08:42.200 --> 08:44.240
Are you all here for pantyhose?

08:45.120 --> 08:47.480
♪♪(The Cure, "Close to Me")

08:48.840 --> 08:52.720
Club Paradise, West Berlin, West Germany

08:53.960 --> 08:56.240
♪♪

09:11.360 --> 09:13.360
(English) Then Matthäus scores a goal

09:13.760 --> 09:15.280
and the whole crowd goes wild.

09:15.680 --> 09:18.640
It was insane, man.
I wish we had pro soccer in America.

09:39.720 --> 09:41.160
Hey, look, there's Alex.

09:41.560 --> 09:42.880
-I'll say hi.
-OK, go.

09:43.280 --> 09:45.040
-Wanna come?
-No, go.

09:45.160 --> 09:47.240
(Crowd cheering)

09:50.920 --> 09:52.640
You know that faggot?

09:53.960 --> 09:57.720
No, he must have me confused.
He's Katie's friend.

10:03.240 --> 10:05.880
Your girl is hot, Private.

10:13.240 --> 10:15.080
Look, I... I'll be right back.

10:19.120 --> 10:21.920
♪♪

10:28.200 --> 10:30.280
(Music fades into background)

10:32.400 --> 10:33.880
(German) What was that, huh?

10:35.000 --> 10:40.000
Come on, Alex. They don't know
I volunteer at an AIDS hospice.

10:41.480 --> 10:43.480
How do I explain that I know you?

10:43.560 --> 10:45.120
Good question. You don't know yourself.

10:45.200 --> 10:49.400
I'm a soldier, Alex.
My first duty is to my country.

10:50.840 --> 10:54.400
Before you serve your country,
you have a duty to yourself.

11:00.240 --> 11:02.000
What are you doing?

11:04.560 --> 11:05.840
I don't know.

11:08.080 --> 11:09.200
You're not ready.

11:16.920 --> 11:19.480
(birds tweeting)

11:20.480 --> 11:24.080
♪♪

11:29.040 --> 11:32.400
Cape Town, South Africa

11:35.920 --> 11:37.200
(Door opens, heavy breathing)

11:37.280 --> 11:39.000
Good morning, Cape Town.

11:39.880 --> 11:41.240
Good morning, Tobias.

11:41.920 --> 11:42.920
How was the reading?

11:43.000 --> 11:44.040
Good, thanks.

11:44.120 --> 11:46.080
The South African ladies went crazy.

11:46.520 --> 11:47.520
Of course.

11:47.880 --> 11:50.840
Right, boys. Let's talk about our mission.

11:51.000 --> 11:52.440
What's that for?

11:52.560 --> 11:54.560
I'm going to chain up Thomas.

11:57.120 --> 12:00.680
Listen up. Here's the entrance,
and Winkelmann's office is here.

12:00.760 --> 12:04.840
We'll enter here. Jason can get
a photo from the other side.

12:04.920 --> 12:07.320
You won't have much time to get the shot.

12:07.640 --> 12:10.240
The shot heard round the world.

12:12.880 --> 12:17.040
Winkelmann Dental & Residence,
Cape Town, South Africa

12:18.040 --> 12:22.040
(Crickets, birds tweeting,
trees rustling, fly buzzing)

12:42.480 --> 12:45.480
I'm actually closed today. But for you...

12:46.040 --> 12:48.720
Thanks for fitting me in
at such short notice.

12:49.840 --> 12:51.400
Have a seat.

12:51.560 --> 12:53.400
♪♪(Classical)

13:00.040 --> 13:02.080
(Mechanical buzz)

13:08.320 --> 13:10.920
(Music gets louder, snapping)

13:19.840 --> 13:21.120
Mouth open, please.

13:24.480 --> 13:26.240
♪♪ (Classical music continues)

13:26.320 --> 13:27.320
Hm-hm.

13:30.080 --> 13:31.080
Huh.

13:34.240 --> 13:35.240
Oh yes.

13:35.360 --> 13:37.440
You have a loose filling.

13:38.200 --> 13:39.720
-I do?
-36, lower left.

13:40.040 --> 13:41.720
We'll put in a new one.

13:41.800 --> 13:42.800
Now?

13:43.040 --> 13:45.360
Don't worry, we'll use local anesthetic.

13:48.120 --> 13:49.320
Are you sure?

13:49.400 --> 13:51.160
I could change a filling blindfolded.

13:51.560 --> 13:52.720
Please don't.

13:53.320 --> 13:55.520
You'll only feel a little prick. Easy.

13:55.600 --> 13:57.280
I need water.

14:06.880 --> 14:08.400
Maybe I'll get it done at home.

14:08.480 --> 14:09.480
Excuse me?

14:10.160 --> 14:13.840
And let a toothache ruin your whole trip?

14:13.920 --> 14:15.560
I can't allow that.

14:17.080 --> 14:19.040
(Music gets louder)

14:23.200 --> 14:25.960
Open your mouth. Close your eyes.

14:33.760 --> 14:34.760
Uh.

14:36.440 --> 14:37.760
♪♪

14:39.240 --> 14:40.600
All done.

14:41.320 --> 14:42.320
Without anesthetic?

14:42.400 --> 14:44.440
Yes, I like to surprise my patients.

14:45.240 --> 14:48.000
But only the very brave ones.

14:49.760 --> 14:51.680
It didn't hurt at all.

14:58.000 --> 15:00.160
Where did you get this filling?

15:00.240 --> 15:03.560
It was long ago. Munich.

15:04.840 --> 15:07.200
♪♪

15:14.480 --> 15:16.360
What'll it be?

15:16.640 --> 15:20.880
Gold, porcelain or something simpler?

15:21.280 --> 15:24.000
I'll take gold. Might as well do it right.

15:25.400 --> 15:26.560
Where's Jason?

15:26.640 --> 15:28.600
West German Embassy,
Cape Town, South Africa

15:28.680 --> 15:30.320
-No idea.
-Without a photographer, we're screwed.

15:30.400 --> 15:32.800
And I still need to give him instructions.

15:33.720 --> 15:35.960
Can any of you work my camera?

15:37.080 --> 15:38.080
Only you.

15:38.160 --> 15:41.040
And you're the only one
who can get the shot we need.

15:42.600 --> 15:44.800
Can you handle it inside without me?

15:44.880 --> 15:46.640
Sure.

15:47.600 --> 15:51.360
Remember, Winkelmann's office is the only
one with a window on this side.

15:51.440 --> 15:53.840
Second floor, third door on the right.

15:53.920 --> 15:55.600
And we only have 30 minutes.

15:55.680 --> 15:59.520
Once Winkelmann arrives,
things will get a lot more complicated.

15:59.640 --> 16:02.480
(Male voice transmitting
over two-way radio)

16:06.560 --> 16:09.960
(Female voice
transmitting over two-way radio)

16:12.120 --> 16:14.560
(English)  We're part of that group.

16:14.960 --> 16:18.520
-Really?
-Yes, really. Isn't it obvious?

16:18.720 --> 16:21.000
(Weak signal over two-way radio)

16:23.080 --> 16:24.400
I guess so.

16:24.800 --> 16:26.440
-Through here.
-Thank you.

16:26.560 --> 16:28.960
(German)  You're 20 minutes early.

16:29.040 --> 16:31.680
-Better too early than too late.
-Mr. Winkelmann isn't here yet.

16:31.760 --> 16:34.160
-But the others are already inside.
-Where did they go?

16:34.520 --> 16:35.520
That way.

16:35.640 --> 16:37.800
Fine. Come with me.

16:39.680 --> 16:42.200
Give me a moment, I'll see where they are.

16:59.200 --> 17:00.200
Well.

17:01.600 --> 17:02.600
Well...

17:03.480 --> 17:05.520
I read that book you gave me.

17:05.600 --> 17:07.120
Did you?

17:07.200 --> 17:09.080
It did not disappoint.

17:10.720 --> 17:12.080
Why...

17:13.120 --> 17:15.680
don't I show you around the house?

17:15.760 --> 17:18.320
♪♪(Elvis Costello
& the Impostors' "I Want You")

17:18.400 --> 17:20.360
♪ You had your fun ♪

17:20.440 --> 17:23.840
♪ Don't get well no more ♪

17:23.920 --> 17:25.880
♪ I want you ♪

17:25.960 --> 17:33.360
♪ Your fingernails go
dragging down the wall ♪

17:33.440 --> 17:40.160
♪ Be careful, darling,
you might fall ♪

17:40.240 --> 17:43.160
♪ I want you ♪

17:43.240 --> 17:48.720
♪ I'm afraid I won't know where to stop ♪

17:48.800 --> 17:50.600
♪ I want you ♪

17:50.680 --> 17:54.400
♪ I'm not ashamed undressing you ♪

17:54.480 --> 17:58.800
♪ Or you undressing ♪

17:58.880 --> 18:03.920
♪♪

18:04.000 --> 18:06.400
♪ I want you ♪

18:06.480 --> 18:12.080
♪ He tossed some tatty compliment
your way ♪

18:12.160 --> 18:14.120
♪ I want you ♪

18:14.200 --> 18:16.920
♪ The one who wants you ♪

18:17.000 --> 18:18.960
Are you looking for something?

18:22.320 --> 18:26.560
♪ I want you ♪

18:30.680 --> 18:32.400
Are we alone?

18:32.560 --> 18:34.080
We've got a maid.

18:34.160 --> 18:35.840
Celeste.

18:36.320 --> 18:38.280
But she's already made the bed.

18:39.720 --> 18:42.280
There's Nelson, the gardener.

18:42.680 --> 18:45.320
But he's in the garden.

18:46.480 --> 18:47.760
Afraid?

18:48.640 --> 18:49.840
Should I be?

18:52.960 --> 18:54.000
Maybe.

18:55.360 --> 18:57.760
(Knocking, distant honking,
voice from two-way radio)

18:59.480 --> 19:04.600
Hi, my colleague spotted you,
and we had to ask...

19:04.680 --> 19:06.440
are you  the  Thomas Posimski?

19:06.520 --> 19:07.640
Yes, I am.

19:07.720 --> 19:09.480
We love your book!

19:09.720 --> 19:11.200
Great, thanks.

19:11.280 --> 19:13.920
Why are you here in the parking lot?

19:14.000 --> 19:15.000
WOMAN:
Where are you losers?

19:15.080 --> 19:16.080
What was that?

19:16.520 --> 19:17.560
Just the radio.

19:18.360 --> 19:21.280
We're a bit late,
we're going to Table Mountain.

19:21.360 --> 19:22.440
I see.

19:23.280 --> 19:24.880
Could I just get an autograph?

19:24.960 --> 19:26.080
Yes, of course.

19:28.840 --> 19:30.440
(Bird chirping)

19:32.440 --> 19:33.440
There.

19:33.520 --> 19:35.480
We learned so much about the East...

19:35.560 --> 19:37.640
How you live. And love there...

19:37.720 --> 19:39.280
Right, thanks, bye.

19:39.360 --> 19:40.600
Thanks.

19:42.360 --> 19:44.120
♪♪

19:58.680 --> 20:00.400
(Door closes in the distance)

20:00.520 --> 20:02.080
What was that?

20:03.440 --> 20:04.920
Must be Celeste.

20:05.960 --> 20:07.680
♪♪

20:16.120 --> 20:17.160
What's going on here?

20:17.840 --> 20:19.960
♪♪

20:26.120 --> 20:27.400
Frank.

20:27.880 --> 20:28.880
No patients today?

20:28.960 --> 20:31.240
I just did my Jane Fonda.

20:31.320 --> 20:33.560
I'm jumping into the shower.
Is everything all right?

20:33.640 --> 20:36.800
I'm missing a yellow folder,
it must be here.

20:37.440 --> 20:40.200
On your desk under today's newspaper.

20:40.280 --> 20:41.320
Oh, really?

20:41.400 --> 20:42.400
Yes.

20:43.800 --> 20:45.680
If I didn't have you!

20:45.800 --> 20:48.200
(Breathing)

20:48.640 --> 20:52.720
You look so good.
I'm late for the office. Otherwise...

20:54.560 --> 20:56.240
A little taste of what's to come...

20:57.880 --> 21:00.680
(motor starts up)

21:08.320 --> 21:09.960
(Accelerating)

21:17.760 --> 21:19.920
(Crackly female voice on two-way radio)

21:20.000 --> 21:21.000
Hm?

21:21.080 --> 21:23.600
(Crackling radio signal,
voice breaking up)

21:24.880 --> 21:25.880
What's happening?

21:25.960 --> 21:28.040
I think something's wrong with Dieter.

21:29.040 --> 21:30.640
♪♪

21:33.160 --> 21:34.160
Shit!

21:36.280 --> 21:38.520
More apartheid?

21:43.920 --> 21:45.560
That's Winkelmann!
Do something, Thomas.

21:47.240 --> 21:48.560
I'll take care of it.

21:48.640 --> 21:50.080
(Camera clicking)

21:53.120 --> 21:54.400
All the best.

21:54.960 --> 21:56.640
(Faint, unnerving shrieking)

21:57.800 --> 21:59.480
(German voices in background)

22:06.760 --> 22:07.800
-Excuse me.
-Yes.

22:07.880 --> 22:10.800
I've lost my way.
Could you tell me where to find...

22:10.880 --> 22:12.400
♪♪

22:13.440 --> 22:14.600
(German) My God!

22:19.080 --> 22:21.080
(Civilian chatter gets louder)

22:22.680 --> 22:24.640
-Power!
-Power to the people!

22:25.040 --> 22:27.240
-Power!
-Power to the people!

22:33.960 --> 22:35.520
I spoke with Fuchs.

22:36.440 --> 22:38.120
(Dogs barking in the distance)

22:38.600 --> 22:40.800
You'll be trained in Berlin.

22:42.600 --> 22:43.880
No. My daughter needs me.

22:43.960 --> 22:46.760
Your daughter is in good hands
with your mother.

22:46.840 --> 22:50.000
Here, at least I can see her.
But from Berlin?

22:50.080 --> 22:53.160
Rose, you're in danger, not your daughter.

22:53.920 --> 22:57.480
Save yourself and take care of her later.

22:57.560 --> 22:59.360
"Later."

23:02.160 --> 23:06.640
No one can help to change South Africa
like my colleagues in Berlin.

23:06.960 --> 23:10.760
They can help you set up
a whole communication network for the ANC.

23:10.840 --> 23:14.360
What if the SADF track me in Europe,
like Olof Palme?

23:14.440 --> 23:19.040
In East Germany,
you'll be safe behind the Iron Curtain.

23:19.920 --> 23:21.360
Go to Berlin.

23:21.440 --> 23:23.160
For your daughter.

23:23.240 --> 23:25.120
And for yourself.

23:25.720 --> 23:27.480
(Distant voices)

23:34.720 --> 23:37.960
Also I couldn't bear it
if anything happened to you.

23:46.920 --> 23:48.720
(kissing, groaning)

23:56.760 --> 23:58.280
(Running water)

24:15.040 --> 24:16.440
(Water stops running)

24:18.280 --> 24:20.200
Can you bring me a towel?

24:24.840 --> 24:26.400
Greetings from General DeGraaf.

24:26.520 --> 24:28.880
(gasping)

24:32.040 --> 24:35.160
♪♪

24:37.720 --> 24:39.880
(gasping)

24:47.560 --> 24:50.760
-Where are the fuckin' weapons?
-I don't know.

25:14.280 --> 25:15.360
(Loud thump)

25:25.240 --> 25:26.920
You might need this.

25:29.400 --> 25:30.680
What about you?

25:31.080 --> 25:32.080
I've got my own.

25:34.640 --> 25:38.360
(South African language)
I'm going to take a long trip.

25:38.640 --> 25:39.920
(Crickets, distant chatter, dog barking)

25:40.160 --> 25:43.120
To a new land with snow.

25:45.960 --> 25:49.520
Yes. I'll buy a warm coat.

25:52.680 --> 25:55.040
Give my love to Granny.

25:58.240 --> 25:59.920
I love you.

26:15.000 --> 26:16.200
(Uneasy laughing)

26:25.080 --> 26:27.120
Everything is changing.

26:28.800 --> 26:31.120
We'll see each other very soon.

26:32.840 --> 26:34.720
If you say so.

26:35.360 --> 26:36.840
♪♪

26:43.720 --> 26:44.960
Uh-uh.

26:49.360 --> 26:50.880
Kleinmachnow, East Germany

26:50.960 --> 26:53.600
MAN (on TV): In Cape Town today,
activists occupied the West German Embassy

26:53.680 --> 26:56.920
to protest the South African
apartheid regime.

26:57.920 --> 27:00.280
(Yelling from TV, piano playing)

27:01.920 --> 27:03.880
Girls, come eat an apple.

27:05.480 --> 27:07.000
Now!

27:07.480 --> 27:09.200
(Voice of news reporter from TV)

27:10.240 --> 27:11.520
Did you fill in everything?

27:11.600 --> 27:15.000
-I'm sending it in. I feel good about it.
-Me, too.

27:15.160 --> 27:16.440
(Dog whimpers)

27:16.520 --> 27:19.680
Why does Sandra
have to go to a special school?

27:19.760 --> 27:21.560
I don't have to, I want to.

27:21.640 --> 27:24.960
Karl Marx is the best math and science
secondary school in Berlin.

27:25.040 --> 27:26.120
How do you know?

27:26.200 --> 27:27.760
Mama went there.

27:29.080 --> 27:30.760
Look! Uncle Thomas!

27:30.840 --> 27:34.320
Among the protesters
was author Thomas Posimski.

27:34.400 --> 27:35.680
My little brother!

27:35.760 --> 27:38.200
I'm only paraphrasing Nelson Mandela
when I say:

27:38.280 --> 27:41.240
"When a man is denied
basic rights and freedom,

27:41.320 --> 27:43.880
he has no choice
but to become an outlaw."

27:44.160 --> 27:45.160
The activists...

27:45.240 --> 27:47.520
AIDS Hospice West Berlin, West Germany

27:47.600 --> 27:52.120
occupied the West German Embassy to draw
attention to the crimes of apartheid...

27:52.200 --> 27:55.440
and denounced trade relations
between West Germany and South Africa,

27:55.520 --> 27:58.880
which have continued
despite the UN embargo.

27:59.320 --> 28:02.240
MAN 2 (on TV): We sat down
for a serious talk with diplomats...

28:02.320 --> 28:07.000
and transformed our embassy
into a symbol of freedom and justice.

28:07.240 --> 28:10.120
We can't just sit around
and knit scarves in parliament.

28:10.200 --> 28:14.240
We must expose the injustice
of apartheid to the world.

28:14.320 --> 28:15.560
Hear, hear.

28:15.640 --> 28:16.640
You know him?

28:16.720 --> 28:17.720
Not really.

28:17.960 --> 28:21.680
I met him at a peace rally, once.
I think it was 1983...

28:22.360 --> 28:23.880
Tim!

28:23.960 --> 28:25.160
(Protests from TV)

28:25.240 --> 28:26.280
Look.

28:26.360 --> 28:30.280
Other people fly around the world
to stand up for their convictions.

28:30.400 --> 28:32.200
(Chuckling)

28:36.480 --> 28:37.640
Other news.

28:38.160 --> 28:40.160
The first Secretary
of the Central Committee...

28:40.360 --> 28:42.080
-Pizza?
-Sure thing.

28:42.520 --> 28:43.800
The dinner is at 8:30.

28:43.880 --> 28:44.960
Almost ready.

28:45.520 --> 28:46.520
How was your day?

28:46.840 --> 28:49.280
Ridiculous. That writer, Posimski?

28:50.200 --> 28:54.800
He came in with his alternative buddies
and made a big scene about apartheid.

28:55.080 --> 28:56.120
-Thomas Posimski?
-Yeah.

28:56.720 --> 28:58.600
Banners and chanting...

28:59.560 --> 29:03.400
In the end, he chained himself to a tree
in front of the embassy.

29:03.480 --> 29:05.160
Where's our rug?

29:05.240 --> 29:06.600
At the cleaners.

29:08.960 --> 29:11.360
I'll top this up before we head out.

29:12.160 --> 29:13.840
I'll be right down.

29:16.320 --> 29:19.320
(Traditional South African chorus singing)

29:40.680 --> 29:42.520
(Singing continues)

29:49.080 --> 29:50.480
What?

29:51.560 --> 29:53.880
Afraid we'll leave you behind?

29:59.800 --> 30:01.440
(Traditional South African singing ends)

30:03.880 --> 30:05.400
(Wind, birds)

30:09.120 --> 30:11.360
So, what was that, honey?

30:12.440 --> 30:13.600
Take a guess.

30:14.000 --> 30:17.040
You told him you do anything for me.

30:20.240 --> 30:21.760
(Portuguese)  Thank you.

30:21.840 --> 30:23.640
(Fly buzzing)

30:24.560 --> 30:25.560
How far?

30:25.960 --> 30:27.560
It's a way to go.

30:36.080 --> 30:37.520
(Slides clicking)

30:37.720 --> 30:40.240
WOMAN: This Max Liebermann
is a great example.

30:40.320 --> 30:44.800
Our Arts & Antiquities Division
found it on a wall in Pankow,

30:44.880 --> 30:46.760
where it had collected dust for years.

30:46.840 --> 30:50.400
Now we're in talks
with a very wealthy collector in New York.

30:51.800 --> 30:56.440
As they say:
One man's trash is another man's treasure.

30:58.600 --> 31:03.920
So next time you visit friends,
make sure to look at their walls.

31:04.320 --> 31:05.480
Thank you.

31:09.240 --> 31:13.720
Here at the Intelligence Division (HVA),
your assets are less material,

31:14.040 --> 31:15.800
but not less valuable.

31:15.880 --> 31:20.840
You mean people's life stories
shouldn't just sit around collecting dust?

31:20.920 --> 31:23.120
The next time you visit friends...

31:23.200 --> 31:27.880
Mrs. Dietrich means that through our work,
we gain unique insight

31:27.960 --> 31:31.840
not only into the lives and minds
of our citizens,

31:31.920 --> 31:34.400
but into the minds of people
all over the world...

31:34.480 --> 31:40.560
Take the Beroxalin medical study.
Normally, patients cost us money.

31:40.960 --> 31:44.280
Now they earn money and are being cured.

31:44.680 --> 31:48.000
It's a win-win situation.

31:48.280 --> 31:50.720
How's the study going,
Comrade Schneider?

31:53.200 --> 31:56.600
Well, twelve patients with
Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease

31:56.680 --> 32:01.320
in the clinic in Potsdam
are taking part in the Beroxalin trial.

32:01.400 --> 32:04.360
Things are definitely going well.

32:04.440 --> 32:08.760
Great. That's the fresh air
I was hoping to bring into this committee!

32:09.160 --> 32:13.680
The next point on our agenda concerns
a note sent down from the very top.

32:13.760 --> 32:17.800
We need to boost morale
in our organization.

32:17.880 --> 32:23.200
We need to remind them of the strength
and beauty of the socialist project

32:23.280 --> 32:28.000
and distract them from changes
taking place across the Eastern Bloc.

32:28.200 --> 32:31.080
(Inhaling, exhaling)

32:33.280 --> 32:36.400
I mean, the more you hear
about starving Romanians...

32:36.600 --> 32:40.600
We shouldn't just think of
our own organization,

32:41.560 --> 32:44.760
but about all the citizens
of East Germany.

32:44.840 --> 32:45.880
Right.

32:50.880 --> 32:54.200
Suggestions for a... smart initiative?

32:55.080 --> 32:57.560
For a cheap initiative.

32:58.440 --> 32:59.440
Hm?

33:01.320 --> 33:04.720
( passing honking, tapping)

33:06.960 --> 33:09.080
♪♪

33:22.880 --> 33:27.120
The Anti-Fascist Protection Wall
turns 25 this year.

33:27.200 --> 33:30.200
We could import fireworks from China.

33:30.960 --> 33:32.960
Everybody loves fireworks.

33:36.640 --> 33:40.880
All our foreign currency up in smoke?
In ten minutes?

33:45.960 --> 33:47.120
(Exhales)

33:49.720 --> 33:51.480
I have an idea.

33:53.440 --> 33:58.320
I'm something of an amateur astronomer.
On the side, of course.

33:59.760 --> 34:03.440
And there's a forest in Prignitz
that's so dark,

34:03.840 --> 34:08.960
you can see more stars at night
than anywhere else I've ever been.

34:09.600 --> 34:11.600
With a telescope,

34:11.920 --> 34:15.640
you can see all the way to the Milky Way!

34:16.600 --> 34:21.480
We could invite our distinguished workers
and farmers to camp out there...

34:21.920 --> 34:24.280
to see the stars.

34:24.920 --> 34:29.680
When you look into the sky at night,
you feel like part of something grand.

34:30.400 --> 34:32.680
There are so many suns.

34:32.920 --> 34:34.920
And moons.

34:35.000 --> 34:36.560
♪♪ (Grand, operatic-orchestral music)

34:36.640 --> 34:41.840
And when you add the possibility
of life on other planets, well,

34:43.120 --> 34:45.200
you don't feel so alone.

34:45.320 --> 34:48.120
No one feels alone in East Germany.

34:52.360 --> 34:54.560
FUCHS: Or we could invest...

34:55.400 --> 35:00.640
in a new cruise ship and revive
the annual cruise for the workers?

35:11.040 --> 35:12.640
How much would that cost?

35:12.720 --> 35:15.680
We could get a used boat from the West
for 120 million.

35:16.400 --> 35:18.680
120 million?

35:20.200 --> 35:24.520
It would be cheaper to let them stay home
and watch  Love Boat  illegally on West TV

35:25.920 --> 35:26.920
But...

35:27.200 --> 35:30.400
I'll give you 90 million.
You find the rest.

35:32.480 --> 35:33.480
Sure.

35:33.560 --> 35:36.640
How's the Würfel & Struth deal
in South Africa going, Comrade Fuchs?

35:38.160 --> 35:39.840
All according to plan.

35:46.760 --> 35:49.040
Ah. Comrade Hartmann...

35:49.360 --> 35:51.080
come here.

35:51.400 --> 35:54.680
My pharma project is extremely demanding.

35:55.120 --> 35:58.440
From now on, I'm delegating
the 1MB microchip project to you.

35:59.120 --> 36:00.880
Yes, I know.

36:01.560 --> 36:04.120
What were they talking about today?

36:06.120 --> 36:09.960
I pitched the Star Forest
in the Prignitz. Nobody checked it.

36:10.040 --> 36:11.160
"Checked it?"

36:11.520 --> 36:14.280
Of course
they went for the  Dream Ship  instead.

36:14.400 --> 36:15.440
The TV show?

36:15.520 --> 36:16.560
No.

36:17.120 --> 36:21.160
A cruise for our distinguished workers
to some tropical brother nation...

36:21.240 --> 36:24.800
Etc. Etc. Naturally without going ashore.

36:25.400 --> 36:27.400
Naturally without going ashore!

36:27.760 --> 36:30.400
And Dietrich
will only cough up half the money.

36:31.760 --> 36:33.680
Well, good luck.

36:33.800 --> 36:34.800
Yeah.

36:36.280 --> 36:40.120
The Star Forest could have been
so much more inspirational.

36:41.720 --> 36:43.360
And so much cheaper!

36:43.440 --> 36:44.440
Hm-hm.

36:56.080 --> 36:57.200
(Pop)

36:58.600 --> 37:00.760
(singing, chanting)

37:18.200 --> 37:21.520
Cuanza Norte, Angola

37:24.720 --> 37:27.600
MAN: Jonas Savimbi, the UNITA leader,

37:27.680 --> 37:31.600
brandishes an American rifle
and proclaims its excellence.

37:31.720 --> 37:32.920
-That's good, that's excellent.
-WOMAN: Excellent?

37:34.320 --> 37:35.920
-Would you like more of them?
-Oh, yes.

37:37.280 --> 37:38.880
I hope that they will get some more.

37:39.720 --> 37:42.560
MAN: Savimbi has no words of comfort.

37:42.640 --> 37:46.160
He says he now has no hope
of establishing

37:46.240 --> 37:48.960
the kind of Angola he dreamed of.

37:49.040 --> 37:55.760
But if it happens, defeat by the MPLA
won't mean the end of hostilities,

37:55.840 --> 37:58.760
but rather
the beginning of a new kind of war.

37:59.280 --> 38:01.400
(dog barking)

38:03.280 --> 38:05.080
(English)  Where the fuck are we?

38:09.920 --> 38:11.120
Gary.

38:16.280 --> 38:17.920
Gary.

38:34.400 --> 38:36.480
(Sound of piston, motor turns off)

38:36.560 --> 38:38.560
MARTIN: Those guys aren't communists.

38:38.680 --> 38:40.520
(Background gibbering, crickets)

38:40.640 --> 38:42.360
They're UNITA rebels.

38:44.920 --> 38:48.600
Those aren't exactly machine parts
in the back either, are they?

38:49.480 --> 38:50.920
What the fuck, Gary.

38:51.800 --> 38:53.920
GARY: You guys know each other, right?

38:54.320 --> 38:56.480
Give me the keys to the back.

39:10.400 --> 39:12.320
(German)  Look who's there, Martin.

39:15.040 --> 39:17.480
General DeGraaf. Holy shit.

39:21.040 --> 39:23.400
Time to find yourself a new lover.

39:24.360 --> 39:26.120
Very funny.

39:28.680 --> 39:32.760
Seven crates of the shoulder-launch
missiles stay here, two stay with us.

39:33.160 --> 39:35.120
(Portuguese)  Tell the others to remove
the seven crates marked with chalk.

39:35.520 --> 39:36.960
(English)  And get a guy a beer.

39:41.560 --> 39:44.920
This oil refinery is a central engine
of the MPLA war machine.

39:45.320 --> 39:47.800
Without it,
they'll run out in a few months.

39:48.200 --> 39:52.360
And now that the money from Moscow
is drying up, they're vulnerable.

39:52.720 --> 39:54.280
Lieutenant-Colonel Kalumba.

39:54.680 --> 39:56.800
He's expecting a shipment
to the oil dispensary this morning.

39:57.200 --> 40:00.200
Let the Germans do the talking
and you'll have no problem getting in.

40:00.600 --> 40:03.000
Kalumba sounds like an infectious disease.

40:03.360 --> 40:04.720
DEGRAAF:
That's one way of looking at it.

40:05.040 --> 40:08.520
He's the commie MPLA Lieutenant-Colonel.
He runs this place.

40:08.920 --> 40:10.880
He's the one paying for the weapons.

40:12.120 --> 40:16.320
Your guys will be here in the truck
with the crates, out of sight.

40:16.680 --> 40:18.040
Once you get to
the control room with Kalumba,

40:18.400 --> 40:21.080
we'll place the blasting charge
next to the naphtha gas pipe

40:21.440 --> 40:22.560
under the cracking unit.

40:22.960 --> 40:24.840
This tank is full of liquid petroleum.

40:25.960 --> 40:27.520
One charge...

40:31.440 --> 40:33.400
and we blow the whole place up.

40:33.800 --> 40:34.960
Boom.

40:35.320 --> 40:37.880
That looks tight, you got a small guy?

40:39.000 --> 40:40.640
(Laughter, bottles clanging)

40:51.200 --> 40:54.040
(Glass smashing, laughter)

40:57.400 --> 40:58.960
(Laughter continues)

41:09.880 --> 41:13.000
(Portuguese) You wanna be a fighter,
right?

41:13.680 --> 41:16.800
Today's your big day, little man.

41:18.160 --> 41:19.680
Get up.

41:22.040 --> 41:24.240
(Contained banging)

41:29.200 --> 41:30.920
(German)  Calm down.

41:34.440 --> 41:36.880
DeGraaf got the weapons
without paying a cent.

41:36.960 --> 41:38.800
Why shouldn't they just kill us?

41:38.880 --> 41:40.760
It depends on what they're planning.

41:41.840 --> 41:43.520
(Crickets, background chatter)

41:55.880 --> 41:58.720
- (English) You're the little guy?
-Roberto.

42:08.680 --> 42:10.480
After Roberto has placed the charge,

42:10.560 --> 42:13.240
you have 15 minutes to
get the hell out of there.

42:13.520 --> 42:14.520
With Kalumba.

42:15.320 --> 42:16.920
Without the Germans.

42:23.840 --> 42:25.840
- (Crowd noise)
-(The Cars, "Tonight She Comes")

43:16.320 --> 43:17.720
(Dance music ends)

43:19.120 --> 43:20.720
♪♪
